Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Halve the @yellow pepper{1}(halved) and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 1cm sized chunks.

Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #medium saucepan{} on a medium high heat.

When hot, add the onion and pepper and cook stirring frequently until tender, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the garlic and cook for a further ~{1%minute}.

Once the garlic has cooked, pour the @water{250%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}.

Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #medium frying pan{} on medium high heat.

Once hot, add the @British chicken breasts{2}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and cook until browned, ~{4-5%minutes} on each side.

Pop onto a #baking tray{}, sprinkle over the @za'atar{1} and roast until cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

  > IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Once bulgur has steamed, carefully fluff it with a #fork{} and stir through the @balsamic vinegar{12}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Transfer the chicken breasts to a #chopping board{} and leave to rest for ~{2%minutes}.

Slice the chicken breasts into 1cm slices.

Share the bulgur between your plates.

Top with the chicken breasts and sprinkle over the coriander. Enjoy!